@node "201" "201/Creating tape files"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

That is not very diffecult. Select an album and open the contents. Click
'Tape all' if you want to select complete selection. The complete selection
will then be ADDED to the tape file allready in memory, whether the file
is empty or not). If you click on just one song title you will only add
that song to the tape file. Inorder for Tape to work properly the
Tape Window has to be open. If it's not open the computer will put up
a requester. No window is No tape. If you're ready with selecting songs 
of an album you can, afcourse, add more from other albums by repeating
the proccess.

If you want to use the Open command, to open a tape file, make sure
the Tape window is visible. If not, select Menu bar/Tape/Activate. If you
do this and you also see 'Clear tape' you have a tape file in memory.
Ps. When the Tape window is open 'Activate' will be 'Deactivate'.
Well, after opening the Tape window you go down to the lower part of
the screen and press & hold the right mouse button. A new menubar will
be displayed. To load a tape file select: Tape/Tape load. A requester
will now ask you to select a file.

Notes:
-The added songs will only be displayed after you have closed the
 contents window.
-You can not add to a tape file with the Tape indicator set.

@{"  --  " link "201"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "202"b}
@endnode

@node "202" "202/Maintaing Tape files"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

After you've either opened or created a new tape file you can apply a few
operation to the selection. Here is a summary of the functions and what
the can do for you:

New:
----
This will erase the tape file from memory.
You will need to do this if you want to create a new tape file (empty).

Merge & split:
--------------
Merge a tape file from disk into current tape file.
Split the current tape file into sections.
See Menus.guide for detail information!!.

Preferences:
------------
Very important. With the preferences you can define the way you are
going to record the selection. See also Menu.guide!

Edit/Clear:
-----------
Erase the tape file or a selection of it.

Edit/Remove:
------------
Remove the tape file or a selection of it.

Edit/Swap:
----------
Swap tape songs, either with or without indicator.

Edit/Insert:
------------
Once the tape indicator is set you can't add song to the file.
With this option you can. See for detailed information Menus.guide.

Edit/Change side:
-----------------
This option will allow you to change the Tape indicator.

Edit/Set style:
---------------
Set the text style for an entry. Bold, italic and underlined are supported.

Selection/Shuffle:
------------------
This will shuffle you tape file randomly.

Selection/Sort:
---------------
This will sort the tape file by alfabetical.

Selection/Info:
---------------
This will give some dry stats about your current tape file

Selection/Calculate:
--------------------
The most important function of all. This will calculate the
selection into a recordably selection. After this operation recording
becomes very easy. See for more info the Menus.guide.

Selection/To printer:
---------------------
This will put your selection on paper.

@{"  ´´  " link "201"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "203"b}
@endnode

@node "203" "203/Closing a tape file"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

If you use the following functions:
 Menu bar/Tape/Deactivate
  or
 Tape menu bar/Exit/Deactivate 
  or
 Window close gadget of Tape window
the tape window will be closed but the tape file will remain in memory.

A tape file is really always closed, no open files. If you have
created a selection or modified one use Tape/Tape save to save the file.
To remove the file from memory use Tape new.

If quit MFS with a tape file in memory the computer will put up a
requester asking you if you are sure about your dessicion.

@{"  ´´  " link "202"b}                                                             @{"  --  " link "203"b}
@endnode

@node "101" "101/Creating Multifile database"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

For more information about Multifile take a look at the menus.guide.
Menus.guide/Extra information/File modes

Before you can start creating a multifile database you need normal MFS
databases. You need atleast two. Do you have two MFS databases then
follow the following steps to create a multifile database.

Select Mutlifile in de Project menu. If you have a project open, close it.
If you are already in the this mode then don't do anything.
Next select Project/Multi new. This will bring up a new window. You see
five long bars, each of them can hold a MFS project name. Click on one
of the bars, the loader will pop up. Now select an .MFS database and click
on OK in the loader to affirm you choice. As you can see the name is
now displayed in the long box. Do this again until you're finished.
Done? Now select the mode you want to use, the sorting mode of your
databases. Remember that all databases must be sorted the same way or 
else everyting will be -not good. Let's get the mode to
'Index: Artist, Title', the mode I always use. Now select OK to go to
the next step. Another window will pop up. You can now enter the name
of the multifile database, an .MFL database. Select the file box. Type
in for example TEST and hit return. As you can see the computer will add
the suffix .MFL to the name. You can also click on the Drawer box, this
will bring up the loader. Anyway, when done select OK to start creating
your MFL database. Select Yes to actually create the database.
The computer will now show a window with some proccesing information.
When done the computer will report that she is ready. Click OK. As you
can see your database has been created and ready for use.

To open a project select menu Project/Multi open.
Now select an .MFL filename and hit the OK button. The database will be
loaded and displayed on the screen.

@{"  --  " link "101"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "102"b}
@endnode

@node "102" "102/Maintanance Multifile database"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

The only thing to maintain the multifile database is that you have to
update it everytime you do someting in the MFS databases. Euhh??
Well, you've create the MFL database out of more than one MFS databases.
If you would input, erase or change an album in one of those databases you
want this to reflect in the MFL database. To do this you need to Update
your MFL database. Also update your MFL database when you reorganize or
sort one of the select MFS databases.

To update your MFL database select Project/Multi update. This window is
identical to the Multi new window. All you have to do is to select Ok
and Yes, the computer will do the rest. Btw, in this window you can also
change the contents of you created MFL database. For example you could add
another MFS database to the list.

@{"  ´´  " link "101"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "103"b}
@endnode

@node "103" "103/Close Multifile database"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

To close the database select menu Project/Multi close.
The computer will automaticly close the project upon quiting.
Change filemode will also close the current project.

@{"  ´´  " link "102"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "104"b}
