@node "104" "104/Other Multifile Functions"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

There not a hell lot you can do in the Multifile mode apart from viewing.
However, some function you can still preform on your selection.

From the Summary menu you can
Goto an album..............By key, artist, title or composer
Search for a song..........Artist, title and/or composer
Create or view Statisics...About the current MFL database
Printer the project........To paper or file

From the Project menu you can
Multi split................Save selections of database to a new database
Multi info.................Some dry data
Single file................Return to single file mode

For more details about these functions you could take a look at the
menus.guide, sections Project menus (multifile) and Summary menu.

@{"  ´´  " link "103"b}                                                             @{"  --  " link "104"b}
@endnode

@node "001" "001/Creating Database"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

Assuming you're screen is plain, no project open. Go to the menu bar and 
select Project New. Now select destanation directory & file (project) name.
Click on the Okay button and the computer will create a new database. The
new project stays open and ready for use. To check how many free keys there
are available (the number of albums you can input) select from the menu bar
Edit/Free keys info. If you do this you will see that you have one free key.
To create more free keys (if you want to input more than one album) select
Edit/Add new keys. Select, for example '10' and click Start. Use free keys
info the check the number of free keys.

To open a project select menu Project/Project open.
Now select an .MFS filename and hit the OK button. The database will be
loaded and displayed on the screen.

@{"  --  " link "001"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "002"b}
@endnode

@node "002" "002/Inputing an album"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

You have to have an open project to input an album.
Select from the menu bar Edit/Manipulations. Now select input with
the right mouse button, the computer will auto search for the first
free key. Now input all the information that the computer asks you to.
Input total time without ':'. Use cursor keys to select the right
medium type and press return to confirm. Select return again if you
don't want the change the selected medium type. You can set the default
medium types in the preferences menu. If you want to connect a sample to
the album you'll have to do that afterwards. Next you input the contents
of the album. Once finished select Save (or make changes and select Save).
Now close the window and you will see that your album is listed on the
screen.

Note:
The current version MFS uses three different kinds of albums.
1...Normal onces, when the artist name is clear
2...Collection, Artist name is 'Collection'
3...Soundtrack, Artist name is 'Soundtrack'
See for more information the menus.guide!

@{"  ´´  " link "001"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "003"b}
@endnode

@node "003" "003/Maintanance"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

Changing album
--------------
To change data from an album select Edit/Manipulation from the menu bar.
Select Change and input the key number of the album you want to change.
Now select a (text) box and change it. To change something in the contents
use the < and > buttons. When done, select Save.

Erasing
-------
To erase an album select Edit/Manipulations/Erase. Enter the key number of
the album you want to erase. If you're sure you want to erase then select
the Erase button at the bottom of the window.

Free keys
---------
Select Edit/Free key info to see how many free keys you have for
inputting albums.

Add new keys
------------
If you don't have enough free keys you can make more with this function.

Sort
----
Menu bar, Edit/Sort index:
You can sort you database with Edit/Sort index.

Second counter
---------------
Menu bar, Edit/Second counter:
With this function you can check the if the total time of the album
matches the total time of all songs of the album added.

Set style
---------
You can use different text styles for displaying the album on the screen
and printer. See also menu.guide for detailed information.
Select Edit/Set style to activate this function.

@{"  ´´  " link "002"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "004"b}
@endnode

@node "004" "004, Other functions"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

Goto album
-----------
Menu bar, Summary/Goto album:
This function will allow you to jump the a specific album of title.

Search record
-------------
Menu bar, Summary/Search record:
If you want to search songs from a certain composer you can use this
function. 

Statistics
----------
Menu bar, Summary/Statistics:
This function will create a host of datas extracted from your database.
You can see, for example, how many albums you have of a certain medium type.
Also displayed is total time all songs, average time etc. etc.

To printer
----------
This will enable you to make a print out of the current project.
Select PPrefs to change the preference settings of the printer and select
Start to begin printing.

@{"  ´´  " link "003"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "005"b}
@endnode

@node "005" "005, Project functions"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

Select menu bar/Project/...

Merge
-----
This will allow you to merge a project into the current project.
This function is great for combining two or more project together.
But you can get a similar effect if you use the Multi file function.

Split
-----
This will allow you the split your project into different sections.
You can choose between a 'copy' effect, where your data will just be copied
into a new database or the 'move' effect, where your data will be copied
to a new database and removed from the current database.

Info
----
This will give you some dry information about the size and status of
the current project.

Multifile
----------
This will set the program into multi file mode. Multi file allows you to
combine a maximum of 5 projects together. See more information the
menus.guide and the special section devoted to multifile.

@{"  ´´  " link "004"b}                                                             @{"  ªª  " link "006"b}
@endnode

@node "006" "006, Close database"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

Use menu bar, Project/Project close to close the current database. This
will allow you the savely exit MFS.
Also if you want to create a new project or if you want to change to
Multi file mode you need to close the current project.

If you exit MFS without closing the current database the computer will
tell you this and will close the current database automaticly.

@{"  ´´  " link "005"b}                                                             @{"  --  " link "006"b}
@endnode

@node "301" "301, Preferences"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

Select Menu bar, MFS/Preferences.

This will bring up a window in which you can set some settings.
Some of them are important, others are less.

The window is devided in 3 parts:
1...Screen
2...Printer
3...Others

Screen prefs
------------
With the screen prefs you can change to colors of the screen and the
mouse pointer. You can also set the screen mode and the default font
to use. If you set a new screen mode the screen will blank for a sec or
so before displaying the new screen mode.

Printer prefs
-------------
In this part you can set the text length of the paper you use. Also page
number (start), pitch style and print quality can be controled from this
section. You can set the header & footer and you can even print the output
to a file (instead of the printer).

Other prefs
-----------
Two functions I want to highlight.
First of all, Auto load:
With this you can select a file to automaticly be loaded into the computer
as soon as you start MFS by its icon. Very handy indeed.
Secondly, Set medium types:
This will allow you to set your own set of medium indicators.
Medium types will tell the difference between a tape and a CD.

Important
---------
After you've made changes to the settings and you want to use them
select USE. If you also want to save them to disk select SAVE. But
remember this, SAVE does not mean USE. So after saving the preferences
you still have to select USE to actually use the new settings.
@endnode

@node "302" "302, Samples"
@{b}----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          Music File System Tutor
                       (c)95/96/97/98   R.F.Bisschop
----------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

MFS uses its own file format for samples. This is due to the fact that
MFS plays real-time from disk, thus saving memory which means that MFS
can also run on older Amiga's.

If you want to use a sample with MFS here is what you should do.
-Sample the file with, for example, Audiomaster IV.
-Save the sample and quit the sampler
-Start SampleCovert from the Tools directory
 See for more information the accomponied document
-Convert sample and quit that great program
-Start MFS and open your project
-Select Edit/Manipulations
-Enter keynumber of the album that is going the be linked with the sample
-Double click on the 'sample' bar
-Select the sample you want to attache and select okay
-Select Save (manipulations)
If you would ask for the contents of the select album you will see that
a new button has appeared, the play button. Select this to hear the sample.

References:
SampleConvert.guide
Menus.guide/extra info/Samples
Menus.guide/Project menus/Edit menus/Manipulations
@endnode

